ibition Spaces on European Modern Art before World War I -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book examines ephemeral exhibitions from 1750 to 1918. In an era of acceleration and elusiveness, these transient spaces functioned as microcosms in which reality was shown, simulated, staged, imagined, experienced and known. They therefore had a dimension of spectacle to them, as the volume demonstrates. Against this backdrop, the different chapters deal with a plethora of spaces and spatial installations: the wunderkammer, the herbarium, the peep show, the spectacle garden, cosmoramas and panoramas, the dépôt/temporary museum, and the alternative exhibition space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEphemeral artxExhibitionsxHistory. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 7aART / History / Romanticism.2bisacsh  aephemeral exhibition spaces, microcosm, spectacle, wunderkammer, herbarium, peep show.1 aBauer, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Dominique, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaklin, Kathryn A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Li-hsin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJovanovic-Kruspel, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcHugh, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulloli, Nirmalie Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurgia, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurgia, Camilla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aP